Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the @21 Day Aged British Sirloin Steaks{2} from your
fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks
(no need to peel). Pop the chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season
with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast the potatoes on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the
@sliced mushrooms{120%g} and season with salt and pepper. Stir-fry until golden brown,
~{5-7%minutes}, then stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Pour in the @water{50%ml} for
the sauce, season again and allow it to reduce by half, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in the
@creme fraiche{75%g}, then remove from the heat and set aside.

When the potatoes have 10 mins left, heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on high heat.
Season the steaks with salt and pepper. When hot, lay the steaks in the pan and fry until
browned, ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another
~{1-2%minutes} on each side for medium-rare.

> TIP: Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more cooked.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest for a couple of
mins.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The steak is safe to
> eat when the outside is browned.

Reheat the sauce and add a splash of water if needed. Stir in the @truffle zest{1}, then taste
and add salt and pepper if necessary. Thinly slice the steak and serve on plates with the
potatoes alongside and the truffle mushroom sauce spooned over. Enjoy!